    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "## Problem¥n¥nWindows path handling has many root/UNC edge cases spread across different code paths: `fnamemodify()`, `vim.fs.normalize()`, etc.¥n¥nThe approach so far has been to patch them one at a time. However, after researching, I found that we're still missing a variety of cases, including (`//?C:/` and `//?/BootPartition`), and doing this will yield an unweildy final outcome if not tracked.¥n¥nI've presented the general order of things below but I'm unsure on one thing: should this discussion be moved to Vim? Already #39805 and #39841 are merged only in neovim, though tracked upstream.¥n¥n## Plan¥n¥n- [ ] Define the Windows path-root cases Neovim should support (should be all of them, hopefully)¥n- [ ] Document (even if here in issues) a behavior matrix for current root handling (i.e. actual vs expected for all functions x windows path cases)¥n- [ ] Refactor Windows root parsing so component-removing code (`vim.fn.fnamemodify`, `vim.fs.normalize()`) agrees on the definition of what a windows root boundary is for all of these cases¥n- [ ] tests obv¥n- [ ] resolve #39721 with documentation¥n",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "I've mentioned this elsewhere, but Python's [`pathlib.PureWindowsPath`](https://docs.python.org/3/library/pathlib.html#pathlib.PureWindowsPath) seems to handle all of these edge cases correctly, and is a great tool to verify correct behavior (especially when you're not on Windows).",
